fields.description:
The default Subversion {{authz}} file has a {{\[/]}} section, and then a {{\[/FOO]}} section for every project (FOO) that differs from these defaults:

{noformat}
[groups]
users = 
developers = 
administrators = 
system-administrators = 
_no-one-at-all = 
[/]
* = r
@developers = rw
@administrators = rw
@users = r
@_no-one-at-all = r
[/FOO]
* = r
@developers =
@administrators =
@users = r
@_no-one-at-all = r
{noformat}

In Administration -> Source -> Project Permissions -> FOO, changes will normally affect the {{authz}} section {{\[/FOO]}}. However, *immediately after creating* the project, manipulating its Subversion permissions changes the {{\[/]}} section:

{noformat}
[groups]
users = 
developers = 
administrators = 
system-administrators = 
_no-one-at-all = 
[/FOO]
* = r
@developers =
@administrators =
@users = r
@_no-one-at-all = r
[/]
* = r
@developers = rw
@administrators = rw
@newprojectgroup = rw
@users = r
@_no-one-at-all = r
{noformat}

  So not only does it change the current project's permissions, but it sets the permissions for various other projects.

Restarting JIRA clears this up, and then manipulating the new project's SVN permissions behaves as expected.

http://stage.jira.com/secure/admin/EditStudioTabs!default.jspa
